The Trojan Horse of Europe
BERKELEY – Europe will have no choice but to bail out Greece.
Emergency funds will need to be allocated.
Conditions will have to be set for it.
The Greek government will make the usual promises.
This should allow the Greek government to service its debt.
The markets will calm down.
The long-term consequences will not be prohibitive, but there will be future problems.
Some will say that the fatal error was allowing Greece to adopt the euro in the first place.
It was nevertheless already evident that the country was not ready.
Her fiscal policy was already out of control when she joined the monetary union in 2001, and her unions were already pushing for Greek wages to align with those in Europe, despite lagging productivity.
But this answer is too simplistic, as such signs of dysfunction are not limited to Greece.
Spain, with a 20% unemployment rate and huge budget deficits, sees in Greece a reflection of its own future.
And if that's not the case, the markets will take care of it.
Portugal and Italy are doing a little better.
These countries, just like Greece, must face significant budget cuts.
Like Greece, they cannot devalue their currency to encourage exports.
Like Greece, they must face a deep recession.
Like Greece, they will be tempted to call for help.
All of this raises a single question: wasn't the real mistake to have created the euro?
Since I was one of the few Americans to support the idea of a European currency, you would be justified in asking me: are you now reconsidering your original position?
My answer is no, creating the euro was not a mistake, but it could well become one.
The Greek crisis shows that Europe is only halfway along the path to a viable monetary union.
If she does nothing, the next crisis could very well make this one seem like a walk in the park.
If she wants to complete her monetary union, Europe will have to create its own emergency financing mechanism.
Today, members of the Union can only provide assistance to Greece by circumventing the regulations that prevent them from granting a loan except in the context of natural disasters or circumstances beyond a country's control.
This exacerbates the uncertainty.
When European leaders offer their help, public opinions and markets tend to question their honesty.
If the problems result from the Lisbon Treaty, then it needs to be amended.
Moreover, aid should not be granted solely under certain conditions, but should be accompanied by temporary control of the national budget by a committee of "experts" appointed by the European Union.
History shows that simple promises made by beneficiary countries are not enough.
Of course, the countries subjected to such measures will express their outrage.
But no one is forcing them to accept this money.
Moral considerations?
Here is your solution.
Note that this would be a much more effective disciplinary mechanism than the defunct Stability and Growth Pact.
One could also ask the following question: how would Californians react if their state temporarily handed over its budget to an expert specifically appointed by President Barack Obama's administration?
In fact, it wouldn't bother them that much.
The expert would not be of Californian origin, but American.
Public opinion would understand that he would act in the interest of the state of California as well as that of the country.
The fact that California would send representatives to Washington, from which this expert's orders would emanate, would reassure them.
Europeans don't do things like that because they first and foremost see themselves as Greeks and Germans.
They do not interfere with the "sovereignty prerogatives" of other member states.
Germany is particularly reluctant, given its history during World War II, especially in Greece.
If Europe really wants to achieve its monetary union, it will have to overcome its past.
This union implies not only stronger economic ties, but also closer political ties.
Those with a solid emergency aid mechanism will really have to account for their actions.
They will have to answer to a strong European Parliament.
The electorate of German Chancellor Angela Merkel hates this kind of rescue because they well know who will be responsible for it.
Germans oppose themselves to anything that resembles European political integration.
But Germany also has its share of responsibility in this crisis.
She wanted an incredibly independent central bank, not required to be accountable, but which today has adopted an excessively expansionary monetary policy, thereby critically worsening the situation of the PIIGS (Portugal, Ireland, Italy, Greece, and Spain).
The enormous current account surpluses of Germany further worsen their situation.
Moreover, its fiscal stimulus measures have not been sufficient to support the European economy.
Germany has significantly benefited from the creation of the euro.
She should do the same.
She should encourage the creation of an emergency loan facility, as well as political integration to make it possible.
She must provide more budgetary support.
Isn't she the best placed to push for a more responsible European Central Bank?
The Greek crisis could be the Trojan horse that leads Europe toward a more accomplished political integration.
One can only hope.
